Object-Like Macros

An object-like macro is a simple identifier that will be replaced by a code fragment. It is called object-like because it looks like an object in code that uses it. It is popularly used to replace a symbolic name with a numerical/variable represented as a constant.

Example

The below example is the illustration of a simple macro i.e. object-like macros.

// C program to illustrate macros
#include <stdio.h>

// Macro definition
#define DATE 31

// Driver Code
int main()
{
    // Print the message
    printf("Lockdown will be extended"
           " upto %d-MAY-2020",
           DATE);

    return 0;
}

Output
Lockdown will be extended upto 31-MAY-2020

